    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-09-14T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-09-14T14:00:00-05:00" n="513"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d513">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/9–1450</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">United States Delegation Minutes: SFM Min–4</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1950-09-14T15:00:00-04:00">September 14, 1950, 3:00 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d513fn1">The complete text of these minutes is scheduled for
                        publication in volume <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>.</note>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Conference of the United States, United Kingdom, and French
                        Foreign Ministers</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">New York, September</hi> 1950</p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">minutes of the fourth meeting held in the waldorf-astoria
                        3:00 p. m. september 14, 1950</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Members</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">Mr. Acheson (US)</p>
                <p rend="center">Mr. Schuman (FR)</p>
                <p rend="center">Mr. Bevin (UK)</p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Present</hi>
                </p>
                <table cols="3" rows="5">
                    <row>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">United States</hi>
                        </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">France</hi>
                        </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">United Kingdom</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Philip C. Jessup</cell>
                        <cell>Henri Bonnet</cell>
                        <cell>M. E. Dening</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>George W. Perkins</cell>
                        <cell>Jean Chauvel</cell>
                        <cell>Sir Pierson Dixon</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Dean Rusk</cell>
                        <cell>M. de Latournelle</cell>
                        <cell>Sir Oliver Franks</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Roland de Margerie</cell>
                        <cell>Sir Gladwyn Jebb</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="italic">Korea</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Acheson</hi> noted that the UN delegations of the three
                    countries had been in constant consultation on the Korean question and were
                    agreed upon the course to be followed in the U.N.<note n="2" xml:id="d513fn2"
                        >See the memorandum agreed upon by the three U.N. delegations dated
                        September 6, <ref target="#pg_704">p. 704</ref>.</note> Unless there were
                    questions to be raised, it seemed unnecessary to discuss the issue further.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Bevin</hi> said that at a later time the United Kingdom
                    wished to discuss the attitude to be taken toward the Syngman Rhee government,
                    but there was no need to raise the issue now.<note n="3" xml:id="d513fn3">
                        <p>The U.S. Delegation Summary Minutes of this portion of the meeting read
                            as follows:</p>
                        <p>“Mr. Acheson noted that the Delegations of the three governments to the
                            United Nations had had a full exchange of views on the subject of Korea
                            and were fully agreed upon the course to be followed in the United
                            Nations with respect to that problem.</p>
                        <p>“The Ministers <hi rend="italic">approved</hi> the understanding reached
                            by their Delegations in this matter.” (Summary Minutes
                            4:795.00/9–1450)</p>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
